# Return One Kind of Concept

A function should return **one kind of thing** — a single domain concept — and
the **return type** should announce it.

`parse_from_string` and `parse_from_file` both return `_Parent`. The caller
always gets "a parent" (success or an error-shaped parent). `run_checks`
returns `_Failures`. The return type is not "list of dicts" or "tuple"; it is
the concept the caller cares about. That keeps the contract clear and the
vocabulary consistent.

Avoid returning ad-hoc tuples or dicts when a named type (dataclass,
NamedTuple, or domain class) would express the concept. The type is part of
the documentation.
